\f0\b\fs36 \cf0 \expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Introduction\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0\fs24 \cf0 UBC Computer science students go through course selection process every semester. Students need to plan their course-load every time to make sure it aligns with their program requirements, workload capacity, and the career outlook they want. The problem is not that this information doesn't exist out there, it does but across dozens of webpages. Every time they have to consult information through sources scattered all across the internet like the UBC Academic Calendar, UBCGrades, RateMyProf, etc.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa298\partightenfactor0

\f0\b\fs36 \cf0 Problem Framing\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\fs24 \cf0 Naive Framing
\f1\b0 : UBC CS students don\'92t have access to the sources that inform their course schedule planning.\

\f0\b Why it\'92s wrong:
\f1\b0  It\'92s not that students don\'92t have access to the information, platforms like UBC Academic calendar, UBCGrades, RateMyProfessor, etc. offer that information.\

\f0\b Sharper Framing:
\f1\b0  UBC CS students have to consult various different sources of information to guide their course planning objectives, often causing them to manually synthesize it themselves, while making sure it fits their program requirements, personal workload capacity and career goals.\

\f0\b Target Market:
\f1\b0  UBC CS students with available elective/non-requirement credits to choose from, who need their course selection to fit their program requirements and workload capacity, while also aligning with their career direction.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa298\partightenfactor0

