\pard\pardeftab720\sa298\partightenfactor0

\f0\b\fs36 \cf0 Key Insights\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\partightenfactor0
\ls1\ilvl0
\fs24 \cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	1	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Requirement fit is a trust problem, not an access problem.
\f1\b0  Students aren't missing sources like the Academic Calendar or Workday - they don't trust their own manual cross-checking enough to be confident a course counts or a plan is complete (S1, S2)\
\ls1\ilvl0
\f0\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	2	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Course quality information is fragmented, not absent.
\f1\b0  Reviews exist across UBCGrades and RateMyProf, but inconsistency between sources - not lack of data - is what prevents students from confidently gauging course quality before enrolling (S5, S6)\
\ls1\ilvl0
\f0\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	3	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Workload risk is invisible until it's too late.
\f1\b0  A schedule that satisfies every requirement on paper can still be unsustainable in practice, and this risk compounds specifically when students optimize for requirement progress without workload visibility (S3, S4)\
\ls1\ilvl0
\f0\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	4	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Manual synthesis is an additional cost of combining all three every term.
\f1\b0  Students already know where to look; what exhausts them even more is re-deriving the same cross-checked answer every registration cycle (S7, S8, S10)\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa298\partightenfactor0

\f0\b\fs36 \cf0 Core problem statement\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0\fs24 \cf0 UBC CS students must satisfy program requirements, personal workload capacity, and course quality every registration cycle, but no consistent source holds course quality information, estimates workload in advance, or synthesizes across these three dimensions - forcing students to manually cross-reference scattered sources and re-derive the same integrated judgment from scratch every term, which costs them significant mental effort.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f0\b \cf0 Objective and Key Results
\f1\b0 \
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\partightenfactor0
\ls2\ilvl0\cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Objective: UBC CS students can do their course schedule planning with accurate information synthesized with less mental strain, while making sure it fits their program requirements, personal workload capacity and course quality/difficulty.\
\ls2\ilvl0\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Key Result 1: % of synthesized requirement and quality statements that match source-of-truth documents when audited - assessed via two criteria: (a) requirement statements checked for deterministic correctness against Academic Calendar/Workday rules, (b) quality statements checked for faithfulness to what UBCGrades/RateMyProf sources actually say, not for objective truth.\
\ls2\ilvl0\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Key Result 2: Reduction in time and/or number of sources consulted per planning session vs. self-reported manual baseline - does accurate synthesis actually translate to faster/less effortful planning, not just correct output.\
\ls2\ilvl0\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Key Result 3: Predictive accuracy of workload estimates - % of courses where estimated weekly hours (self-reported by prior students) falls within [X hours] of a subsequent student's actual reported hours, validated and refined via an ongoing feedback loop rather than a fixed launch-day number.\
\ls2\ilvl0\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Key Result 4: NPS ("How likely are you to recommend Academic OS to a friend?"), reported only alongside KR1's accuracy rate.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa298\partightenfactor0

\f0\b\fs36 \cf0 Solution\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0\fs24 \cf0 Academic OS aggregates and cross-references the sources UBC CS students already consult separately - Academic Calendar and Workday for program requirements, UBCGrades and RateMyProf for course quality - into a single synthesized output, replacing the manual cross-checking students currently do themselves every registration cycle.\
A student provides their program, year, credits remaining, and requirement gaps once. Academic OS returns a single synthesized recommendation: a set of courses with the reasoning for each shown alongside it - which requirement bucket it satisfies and why, and what its quality signal is across sources - rather than raw data the student has to interpret themselves.\
At launch, Academic OS synthesizes only what already exists across these four sources; requirement fit and quality fit are the two dimensions the Core Problem Statement treats as co-equal and immediately actionable, and together they're what Key Result 1 (synthesis accuracy) and Key Result 2 (time/sources reduction) are built to measure. This is a complete, working product on its own, not a partial slice of a larger one.\
Workload capacity is deliberately not part of this phase - not a choice to hold it back, but a data dependency. No consistent source-of-truth for weekly time commitment exists yet; Academic OS would need to generate that data itself, through self-reported hours from students who've taken the course, and the earliest that data can exist is the end of the first term the product is live. Key Result 3 (workload predictive accuracy) is a Phase 2 KR by design, not a launch metric with a slow start.\
Two related capabilities are deferred for the same reason of sequencing, not necessity: swap/edit of an individual recommendation without resubmitting full inputs, and career-goal course mapping (already addressed in the Design Decision Log - every candidate data source failed the product's verifiability standard). Both sit on top of a flow that is already complete without them.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa298\partightenfactor0

\f0\b\fs36 \cf0 Design Decision Log\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\fs24 \cf0 Decision: Career-goal course mapping deferred to Phase 2/3 (reaffirmed)
\f1\b0 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f2\i \cf0 Considered:
\f1\i0  Re-including career-goal alignment (Insight: students unsure which electives serve their career interests) in MVP scope, prompted by re-reading raw user research and finding roughly equal representation (3 of 10 entries) alongside course-quality insights.\

\f2\i Why it stayed deferred:
\f1\i0  Every candidate data source for grounding a course-to-career mapping fails the product's core standard - verified, live synthesis rather than plausible guessing:\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\partightenfactor0
\ls3\ilvl0\cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Self-authored mapping (personal knowledge) - opinion, not verifiable data; inconsistent across authors\
\ls3\ilvl0\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 LLM-generated mapping - pattern-matched plausibility, not grounded fact; the exact failure mode Academic OS is positioned against in the Competitive Landscape section\
\ls3\ilvl0\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Self-labeled "personal advice" feature - doesn't resolve the credibility gap, just relocates it into the product experience itself\
\ls3\ilvl0\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Real professor interviews - highest-quality option, but still opinion (professors lack labor-market outcome data), inconsistent with the case study's existing research-integrity boundary (no real interviews elsewhere), and not feasible within the current build timeline\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f2\i \cf0 Why frequency in the research table didn't override this:
\f1\i0  Evidence volume (how many students mentioned a pain point) answers a different question than feasibility (whether the product can ground a solution to it in verifiable data). Insights 1 & 3 map cleanly to existing structured sources (Academic Calendar, Workday, UBCGrades, RateMyProf); career-goal mapping does not.\

\f2\i Implication:
\f1\i0  Reinforces the product's differentiation thesis - Academic OS competes on grounded, verifiable synthesis, not on capability breadth. Including an ungrounded feature to chase completeness would undercut the exact claim the product is built on.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f0\b \cf0 Decision
\f1\b0 \
: Excluded trust-in-tool-output from the Core Problem Statement.\

\f0\b Reasoning
\f1\b0 \
: Research (S1, S2) shows distrust in students' own manual cross-checking - not distrust in a hypothetical automated tool's output. No interview data exists on whether students would trust a system's synthesized recommendation. Claiming this as a solved or unsolved problem would be unsupported by evidence.\

\f0\b Status
\f1\b0 \
: Open question - flagged for future user testing, not assumed either way.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0
